      m_Calls: []
  m_text: A longitudinal wave is a wave whose vibrations travel along the direction
    of the wave. Thus, if a wave is moving to the right, the vibrations also move
    to the right. This wave creates areas of compression where loose molecules clump
    together during transmission at certain intervals. This wave travels fastest
    in a solid, which becomes nonexistent in a vacuum, where no molecules can support
    the wave. An example of this wave is sound.
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: -4890204404628985631, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
