  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "We all know that everything is powered, or driven, by something. That
    something is what we call energy. Stereotypically, we define it as the capacity
    to do work. But, it is not always the case.\n\nEnergy is best defined as the
    property that objects need to transfer in order to perform work. Since there
    is transfer involved, energy can neither be created nor destroyed. It can only
    change forms, which allows a body to perform work on another body. Its unit is
    also joule. \n\nThere are two basic forms of energy: kinetic and potential. Kinetic
    energy (usually abbreviated as KE or T) is the energy translated in motion (i.e.
    it is the energy observed in motion). It is also best explained as the energy
    an object possesses because it is moving. \nFormula: T = (1/2) mv^2, where m
    = massand  v = speed (velocity if direction is indicated).\r\n\nThe other form
    of energy, the potential (abbreviated as U or PE), is the energy observed from
    rest, either from its position to other objects, stresses within itself, and
    many more.\n\nPotential energy comes in various forms, but here, we shall be
    discussing two (2) forms of it: gravitational and elastic. Gravitational potential
    energy (abbreviated as U_gg) is the potential energy stored due to a change in
    height. Simply put, the higher the object, the higher its potential energy. \nFormula:
    U_gg = mgy where m = mass, g = acceleration due to gravity and y = height.\n\nThere
    is also the other form of potential energy, the elastic potential energy. The
    elastic potential energy (abbreviated as U_e) is the potential energy stored
    by an object as it gets pulled apart or compressed. Elastic potential energy
    exists if an elastic object is being pulled at its ends, such as a rubber band. 
    \nFormula: U_e = (1/2) kx^2 where k = spring constant (in N/s^2) = and x = displacement
    of spring.\n\nEnergy is a concept that is neither created nor destroyed. It only
    transfers, and changes form, from one body to another. Therefore, conservation
    is observed. This conservation rule is known as the Law of Conservation of Energy.\n\nThis
    is one of the fundamental conservation laws in Physics that explains that the
    total energy of the system is constant, which helps us tackle problem- solving.
    There are two classifications of force: conservative and non-conservative. A
    conservative force is a force whose work done between two given points is independent
    from the path taken by the work itself.\n\nIf a force, however, follows the path
    the work has formed from two points, or if the force cannot associate itself
    with potential energy, the force then is non-conservative. \n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: -4890204404628985631, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
