      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "The transverse wave is a wave whose vibrations travel perpendicularly
    from the wave\u2019s direction. It travels at certain intervals and is usually
    drawn like a sine curve. It travels the fastest in a vacuum, which becomes nonexistent
    in a solid, where the matter only absorbs the energy carried by the wave. An
    example of this wave is light, which is made up of two (2) perpendicular waves
    coexisting as one beam of light."
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
