  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'We always experience fluids every single day. But, if we are to study
    how the term "fluid" is understood in the vernacular, we always mean it as a
    liquid. To Physics, however, fluid is any substance that characterizes flow,
    i.e., any substance that has no rigid structure is amorphous and conforms to
    the shape of the receptacle it is in.


    In its broadest sense, a fluid can
    either be a liquid or a gas. If we are to recall our basic science, a liquid
    has no shape but is denser than a solid, whereas a gas has no shape and is the
    least dense of the four (4) states (except plasma, which is lighter and has more
    energy). This is because the atoms in both liquid and gas can freely move, as
    they have higher energy compared to a solid.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: -4890204404628985631, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
