  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Scientific Notation is a way scientists compress extremely large or small
    numbers into manageable values widely understood by many. Although there are
    numbers that do not need such configurations, such as 125 or 0.12, scientific
    notation enables scientists to read and organize values that can help in their
    research.\n\nWriting numbers in scientific notation has two (2) advantages:\r\n1.
    It saves space, especially when handling extremely large amounts of data using
    complicated formulae.\r\n2. It allows for faster unit conversions.\n\n\rGuidelines
    on how to write in Scientific Notation.\r\n1. Coefficient must be greater than
    or equal to one (1), but less than 10, for there must be only one (1) nonzero
    digit.\n\r\nExample:\r\n1.23 \xD7 1023\t \tThis is CORRECT.\r\n12.3 \xD7 1022\t
    \tThis is WRONG.\r\n0.123 \xD7 1024\t        This is also WRONG.\n\r\n2. The
    base is always 10.\n\r\n3. Exponents in the scientific notation represent the
    number of digits the decimal point has crossed, and are either positive or negative
    only.\r\n     a. The exponent is POSITIVE if the decimal point moves to the left.
    This means that the number has a large     value (see Example a).\r\n     b.
    The exponent is NEGATIVE if the decimal point moves to the right. This means
    that the number has a small  value (see Example b).\r\n     c. Although fractional
    exponents represent radical values, there is no radical notation in the scientific
    notation.\nExample:\r\n     a. 1.23 \xD7 1023 is 123,000,000,000,000,000,000,000
    when expanded.\n     b. 1.23 \xD7 10\u221223 is 0.0000000000000000000000123 when
    expanded.\r\n\nOperations involving Scientific Notations are straightforward.
    This method utilizes the basic four (4) operations of Mathematics when handling
    decimal and exponent values.\n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: -4890204404628985631, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
