  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: 'Rectilinear Motion is defined as motion along a straight line, with motion
    being defined as the change in position over a given time. By definition, it
    means that everything behaves in a linear manner, so the objects and scenarios
    involved are only moving along one (1) of the three (3) known axes that we use
    (x, y, z). An example would be a car driving along the straight highway, without
    any other cars interfering its movement.


    There are several formulas we
    use to show motion. But before we go into that, we need to define a few key terms
    used in this topic:


    Distance - the total measured length between two (2)
    given points. Simply put, if we use a simple racetrack, it is measured from Start
    to the Finish line.


    Displacement - the measured mean distance covered between
    two (2) specified points. Displacement is a certain distance at any given two
    (2) points. So, going back to the track, the displacement could be from Start
    to the middle, middle to the Finish line, or it could also be the average distance
    between the Start and the Finish line; used interchangeably with distance.


    Time
    is the progression of events occurring between instances. It is something we
    need to prove that there is a progression between events, such as from walking
    to running, jogging from point A to B, and so on.'
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
