  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: f4688fdb7df04437aeb418b961361dc5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Force is defined as an influence that tends to change an object\u2019s
    state of motion when left unopposed. It can also be defined as the strength or
    energy which is the result of physical action or movement. Force unit is Newtons
    (N). Formula: F = m*a.\n\nThe net force is the difference between the applied
    force and the countering force acting upon the object and is the sum of all different
    forces acting on an object, Formula:  F_net = F_A + F_B. \n\nWeight (F_w) is
    the force exerted by gravity on the object, represented by the formula, F_w =
    mg, with g is the acceleration due to gravity going down.\r\n\nNormal Force (F_n)
    is the force acting against weight, which is always perpendicular to the surface
    the object is resting upon (going up).\n\nFrictional Force, or friction (F_f),
    is the resistance of a surface or an object acting upon another object in contact
    with it (going left), Formula: F_f = u \xD7 F_N.\n\nApplied Force (F_app) is
    the force directly applied to an object (going right).\r\n\nThere are two (2)
    kinds of friction to be considered. First is static friction, the friction in
    which an object needs to overcome in order to move. Kinetic friction, on the
    other hand, is the friction experienced by moving surfaces interacting on each
    other.\r\n"
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_sharedMaterial: {fileID: -4890204404628985631, guid: ed9fe41215e4a2c4a9fa581443855244, type: 2}
  m_fontSharedMaterials: []
  m_fontMaterial: {fileID: 0}
  m_fontMaterials: []
